\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires occur in hot and dry conditions that also occur during heatwaves.
 Intuitively, a train of thought would be that bushfires happen during heatwaves.
 This co-occurrence is not common.
 This chapter describes the typical climate signature of bushfire and heatwave
 weather patterns.
 This study focuses in Victoria during the period 1961-2011.
 This investigation is important because this is a region endangered by
 extreme bushfires and heatwaves.
 Forecasting efforts can benefit from a deeper understanding of their synoptic
 differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter comprises five sections.
 Section two describes the data and methods of this research.
 Subsequently, a comparison between BF and HW weather patterns is presented.
 Section four discuses the results.
 The last section summaries the chapter.
\end_layout

