\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Daily weather patterns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different weather patterns produce bushfire and heatwave events in Victoria,
 Australia.
 The key feature of extreme fire weather in southeast Australia are cold
 fronts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Reeder1987,Reeder2015"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, a high-pressure system in the Tasman Sea is the key
 pattern producing heatwaves in this region 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pezza2012,Parker2014a"

\end_inset

.
 Their co-occurrence can produce catastrophic fire events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mills2005,Engel2013"

\end_inset

.
 However, after disentangling bushfire and heatwaves events, a synoptic
 climatology shows that their differences prevail.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires and heatwaves do not usually occur simultaneously in this region.
 Extended periods of low relative humidity and cold fronts contribute to
 bushfire occurrence.
 These patterns may have a greater influence than short-term anomalous heat
 produced by heatwaves.
 It suggests that different mechanisms drive these two types of events.
 The discussion of the underlying mechanisms will focus on the influence
 of climate modes of variability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discussing geopotential patterns can illustrate different mechanisms in
 action during bushfire and heatwaves.
 Overall, heatwaves show stronger anomalies than bushfires.
 Bushfire events exhibit strong positive anomalies between Australia and
 Antarctica.
 In contrast, heatwave events present a precursor wave train in the Indian
 Ocean.
 The synoptic forcing is weaker for bushfires.
 This forcing appears to be associated with positive pressure anomalies
 within Antarctica.
 Heatwaves are connected to negative pressure anomalies in the same region.
 These differences suggest that the Southern Annular Mode could play a major
 role on a daily time-scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To expand on this discussion, it is important to analyse the sensitivity
 of the results.
 Using an alternative bushfire database or heatwave definition could yield
 different results.
 Thus, Chapter 6 reproduces these results using alternative data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Seasonal weather patterns 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires and heatwaves weather significantly differ in the behaviour of
 relative humidity.
 The preconditioning process leading to bushfires is more intense compared
 to its heatwave counterpart.
 Victoria is a dry region from September to February.
 A positive Indian Ocean Dipole mode has been associated with this process
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 A slight area of negative anomalies in Victoria is present in spring during
 heatwaves.
 However, it is important to highlight how the rest of Australia becomes
 more humid from spring to summer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The seasonal weather differences perhaps are best illustrated comparing
 the upper atmosphere circulation patterns.
 For bushfire seasons, the climate signature at the 300 h-Pa level presents
 strong westerly anomalies south to Australia.
 These statistically significant anomalies could be linked to high baroclinicity
, and therefore, vigorous frontal activity.
 This result supports the important role of cold fronts in bushfire occurrence
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Reeder1987,Reeder2015"

\end_inset

.
 Interestingly, heatwaves present an opposite pattern, with easterly anomalies
 especially over Victoria.
 This reversal of the 300-hPa zonal wind pattern requires further analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The anomalous areas found in the composites could be used to design a seasonal
 bushfire index.
 Such an index could contribute to anticipating extreme bushfire seasons
 in Victoria.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

 have already suggested this possibility using climate variables and ENSO
 indices.
 Additionally, the analysis of weather patterns conducive to lightning ignition
 could demonstrate forecasting skill.
 This gap is an exciting avenue for further research.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ENSO, bushfires and heatwaves 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On average, ENSO's influence over bushfire events in Victoria is moderate.
 The SST anomalies in the tropical Pacific Ocean reveal warming conditions
 (+ 0.5 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C) during these events.
 These results are consistent with the two databases used (see Chapter 6).
 Although, only the NINO1+2 and the NINO3.4 regions showed statistical significan
ce.
 Paradoxically, the correlations between the bushfire time series and the
 SOI were weak.
 This result suggests that the oceanic component of ENSO has a greater influence
 over bushfires (see chapter 5).
 This moderate influence has already been proposed by
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 ENSO has a greater influence over bushfires in other regions in Australia
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nicholls2007a,Harris2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, heatwaves in Victoria do not seem linked to any particular
 ENSO phase.
 Most heatwaves occur during neutral ENSO events, a result that agrees with
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Boschat2014"

\end_inset

.
 The results show this is independent of the heatwaves definition adopted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role that the ocean might exert in the dynamics of bushfires and heatwaves
 is of particular importance.
 The dynamics behind the differences between these phenomena should be further
 investigated in this direction.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sadler2012"

\end_inset

proposed an experiment to measure the impact of perturbed SSTs in the Tasman
 Sea in the lead-up to heatwaves.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fiddes2015"

\end_inset

 discussed the role of SST in the enhancement of the cold front and heatwave
 leading to 'Black Saturday'.
 It would be interesting to attempt a similar study that investigates the
 influence of SST in fire weather days not linked to heatwaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relatively short period of analysis is a limitation in this study.
 Heatwaves in this region can be computed from the early years of the century.
 However, the development of a robust bushfire database for the first half
 of the 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century in Victoria is a scientific gap.
 This investigation requires proxy data such as fire history studies and
 paleoclimate records.
 Unfortunately, this endeavour was out of the scope of this research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires and heatwaves are dangerous natural hazards in Australia.
 Above-average air temperature anomalies characterise them both.
 However, they differ in several other climatological aspects.
 This chapter compared the weather patterns associated with these events
 in Victoria, Australia.
 The investigation comprises the computation of daily and seasonal anomaly
 composites for the period 1961-2011.
 The results show that only 13% of bushfires co-occurred with heatwaves.
 A humid Australia characterises heatwaves while bushfires exhibit the opposite
 pattern.
 On average, an 'El Niño' pattern dominates the tropical Pacific Ocean during
 bushfires.
 On the other hand, heatwaves usually occur during neutral ENSO conditions.
 These results were obtained using weather station as well as reanalysis
 data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter 5 explores fire weather weather variability in Victoria in the 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 The investigation uses seasonal metrics of the Forest Fire Danger Index
 (FFDI).
 It also propopses a seasonal bushfire index based on the results of this
 chapter.
 Finally, the next chapter investigates climate-bushfire relationships.
 The aim is to establish the skill to seasonally forecast extreme fire seasons
